<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ910121-0118</DOCNO><DOCID>910121-0118.</DOCID><HL>   SPS Technologies   Sets Special Charge   Due to Consolidation</HL><DATE>01/21/91</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), NO PAGE CITATION</SO><CO>   ST</CO><IN>DIVERSIFIED INDUSTRIAL (IDD)</IN><LP>   NEWTOWN, Penn. -- SPS Technologies Inc. saidfourth-quarter results would include a charge of about $5.3million to cover consolidation of manufacturing activitiesand related work force cuts.   The aerospace and industrial-equipment maker added thatexclusive of the restructuring charge, it expects to reportafter-tax losses from continuing operations for both thefourth quarter and year. It expects to report operatingprofit for 1990.</LP><TEXT>   SPS officials declined to estimate the size of the losses.They declined to specify the timing or extent of therestructuring moves or payroll reductions, saying only thatthey are intended to improve manufacturing efficiencies andreduce costs.   `The facilities haven't been informed,&quot; said Arthur B.Belden, chief financial officer, in explaining why cutsweren't detailed. He said some cuts had already been made,while others were under way or planned. SPS employed 5,800people worldwide at the end of 1989.   The company attributed its expected financial losseslargely to weakness in demand for its industrial fasteners,rising costs and &quot;the inability to record a full tax benefiton certain losses.&quot;</TEXT></DOC>